(2:9) In the quarkonium rest frame, the matrix element has only a weak dependence on x; x0, and y, this dependence is controlled by the small scale M v, while the dominant timedependence is given by (2.9) and the correction to this is controlled by the scale M v2.

5

The difference between the space- and time-dependences naturely leads to use NRQCD to make the expansion in v. The another advantage of using NRQCD is due the recent progress on lattice study, where nonperturbative properties of a quarkonium can be well studied with lattice NRQCD[11].

3. The Small Velocity Expansion In this section we will work in the quarkonium rest frame. To avoid confusions due to too many notations and bookings we still use the same booking for momenta as in Sect.2. Finally we will express our results in a covariant form. In the expansion we will have space-time derivative @_, we will automatically substitute it with the covariant derivative D_, since this is the plausible way to maintain the gauge invariance. Before going to the expansion we discuss briefly how the expansion of the original QCD Lagrangian in the power of v to obtain NRQCD.

We write the Dirac field Q(x) as

Q(x) = e\Gamma iMtQ+(x) + eiMtQ\Gamma (x); (3:1) as discussed in the last section, the four component field Q+(x) and Q\Gamma (x) have a weak dependence on x. With the equation of the motion these fields take form:

Q+(x) = P+h+(x) \Gamma ifliDi2M P+h+(x) + O(v2) Q\Gamma (x) = P\Gamma h\Gamma (x) \Gamma ifliDi2M P\Gamma h\Gamma (x) + O(v2);

(3:2)

here P\Sigma = (1 \Sigma fl0)=2, h+(x) and h\Gamma (x) are certain four component fields. Since there are always the combination P\Gamma h\Gamma (x) and P+h+(x) appearing in (3.2), we use two twocomponent fields and O/ to denote P+h+(x) and P\Gamma h\Gamma (x). The Lagrangian for the two-component fields upto v2 can be easily obtained, which is the Lagrangian of NRQCD:

LNRQCD = y(iD0 + D

